  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Psychosocial and Advocacy Interventions for the Protection of Human Rights of Earthquake-Displaced Populations</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">An assessment conducted in seven camps revealed 26,018 vulnerable internally displaced persons (IDPs) in need of accompaniment and protection. The displaced did not understand their rights and had little control over their lives. Through workshops, JRS taught them about human rights and principles of protection. We provided group therapy sessions and pastoral services like the Eucharist and baptisms for Catholic camp residents. The program gave psychosocial support to 23,000 people and pastoral services to 1,400 people. Our camp coordination committees empowered the IDPs by giving them a stake in the camp operation. The committees utilized skills acquired in management and planning trainings to organize camp activities, such as sporting and International Women&#x2019;s Day events. These peer-led activities helped foster a sense of community among people who wrestled daily with loss, displacement, and an uncertain future.</narrative>
  </description>
